University of Santo Tomas, EXPLAIN!

Sobrang lala ng management nyo ng opening ceremony ng UAAP S88!

UNANG UNA. 3:30 nakapila na kami sa gate. Ang announcement, 6:30 pm magsasara ang gates pero 5:30 pa lang isinara nyo na kaya daan-daang estudyante AT ATHLETES ang nastranded sa España. Sinimulan nyo ang program na maraming kabataan ang nasa labas. 

PANGALAWA. 6:30 na. Sumisigaw na kami na buksan ang gate kasi nagkakastampede na sa Gate 2. Pati mga atleta hindi nyo pinapasok kahit nagmamakaawa na. MGA SECURITY GUARDS NYO, PINAGTATAWANAN PA KAMI. 

PANGATLO. 7pm na. NAGSSTAMPEDE NA ANG TAO SA GATE 1 KASI DOON KAMI ITINURO. Inabutan na kami ng ulan pero yung mga security guards nyo, galit pa. Yung mga organizers nyo, nanonood lang. 

Yung kasama ko, hinimatay— nagcollapse na. Aba, pati companion ayaw nyong pasamahin kung hindi pa pipilitin ng mga tao sa likod? 

UST, THIS IS NOT SOMETHING YOU CAN SIMPLY PUT OFF AS AN OVERFLOW NG CROWD. 

YOU PRINTED LOTS OF TICKETS PERO ANG SAGOT NG MGA GUARDS, PUNO NA PO? Hindi nyo naestimate ang crowd na pupunta sa inyo?

INUULAN NA KAMI SA TABI NG ESPAÑA, YUNG ILAN AY NASA HIGHWAY NA PERO SINARA NYO YUNG GATE DAHIL KASALANAN DAW NG MGA NASA LABAS? Lahat kami may tickets, at lahat kami matiyagang pumila UNTIL NAGDECIDE KAYO NA ISARA ANG GATES UNANNOUNCED.

Inagahan nyo ang cut-off ng entrance; HINDI kayo nagannounce kung magpapapasok pa ba kayo o hindi para makauwi na ang iba; AT TINATAWANAN PA NG IBA NYONG GUARD habang nakikiusap at nababasa sa ulan ang mga estudyante.

UNACCEPTABLE.

This is for the freshies who feel frustrated about getting a ticket. Big events like opening ceremony ay unahan talaga especially sa UST gaganapin. Honestly, swerte pa nga tayo kasi binibigay sa atin for free, sa ibang univs may bayad pa.

1. Sa mga nag tatanong kung kailan nagiging available yung tickets, tickets usually become available 1–3 days before the game/event. So once UE announces tickets for a game, that’s also when the UAAP opening tickets are out.

2. Not all tickets are with the PE Department. A lot of them are with PE profs and they also give them out for free. Some students even got multiple tickets from their professors. (5 tickets per person pa nga eh) 

3. Keep in mind that UE has other campuses, not just Manila. So when they say 1,000 tickets, hati yan between UE Manila and UE Caloocan, plus yung mga tickets na hawak ng PE profs. So konti na lang talaga natitira. 

4. Scalpers are EVERYWHERE. Believe it or not, they will always find ways to sell tickets that were meant to be free, even to people outside UAAP schools. Para lang sa pera.

Additional info: You can’t enter without both a ticket and a school ID na proof na from UAAP school ka. So if you buy from scalpers and you’re not from a UAAP school, the ticket is basically useless. Sayang lang din. Napunta na sana sa ibang kapwa student.

I don’t usually write stuff like this, but I’ve been thinking about it for a while. Every time I check this page, I notice how many of the posts about being gay are written as jokes. Most of the time they’re sexual and every time I see it, I just feel sad. Maybe for a lot of you, it’s nothing. It’s just something to laugh at. But for someone like me (i’m bi) it doesn’t just disappear after reading it. It stays with me. It makes me think about how people in this school might look at me, or at anyone who’s not straight, and automatically reduce us to those same jokes. And it hurts in a way that’s hard to explain. Because the truth is, being gay isn’t about sex. It’s not about being dirty, or weird, or any of the things people here like to laugh about. It’s about love. It’s about finding comfort in yourself when the world makes it hard. It’s about liking someone in the same simple, human way that straight people do, but always with that extra layer of fear, fear that people will twist it into something disgusting.
I read the things people post and I just keep wondering if anyone thinks about what it feels like for us. To constantly see your identity turned into something shameful. To know that in the eyes of your classmates, maybe even your friends, you’ll always be some kind of punchline. It makes me feel small, and it makes me feel like no matter what I do, how hard I study or how kind I try to be, people will only ever see the joke, never the person.
I’m not writing this to call out anyone, or to pick a fight. I’m not even angry at all. I’m just tired. I’m tired of watching love get turned into something ugly when I know it isn’t. Maybe this won’t change anything. But maybe someone will read this and think twice. And for me, that would already mean a lot. Anyways, that's all for now. God bless you all

a message from DLSU student

Anyone here into powerlifting or just lifting heavy? We are planning to start an unofficial powerlifting team for UE students who train squat, bench, and deadlift. We can train together, share tips, programs, and even join competitions. NCAA will be starting their own powerlifting events sometime soon, UAAP doesn’t yet, but why not start something here at UE? The goal is to build a school powerlifting team that represents UE and to compete in inter-school events. If you’re interested leave a comment below!

Medyo nalilito ako — nagbigay kayo ng 1k tickets for each UAAP school pero may cutoff pala? So ano pa ang silbi ng ticket kung hindi rin papapasukin yung ibang students?

I was blessed enough to attend, pero naaawa ako sa dami ng UAAP students na maayos namang sumunod sa rules, tapos yung iba pa nagbayad pa ng malaki just to witness the opening, pero hindi pinapasok. As far as I know, walang official post na may cutoff time (nalaman ko lang kasi may friends akong taga-UST). Not trying to shame UST — the event was successful despite the weather — pero sana if may cutoff time talaga, maipost na in advance para hindi na rin umasa yung ibang students. Besides, kung may cutoff man, hindi ba dapat applicable lang yun sa mga taga-UST since sila yung expected na sobrang dami? Hindi naman sa special treatment, pero mas logical na may oras lang sila hanggang kailan pwede pumasok — hindi para sa mga taga ibang school na limitado na nga yung tickets tapos ipagkakait niyo pa.

Kasi imagine, 36k daw yung pumunta pero majority ng taga-ibang schools napilitang magstay sa labas. Kung ganun din lang pala, sana sinabi niyo na lang na for UST students lang yung event, para hindi na nag-effort at gumastos yung iba. And if expected niyo na madami talaga pupunta na taga-UST, sana binawasan niyo na lang yung number of tickets allotted sa ibang schools para fair at para maiwasan yung ganitong problema.

Shoutout sa inyo, UE. Kuripot niyo pa rin. Nagcocomplain kayo na hindi na kilala ang UE, pero kahit sa simpleng pagbibigay ng tickets para dumami ang supporters ng mga athletes, mas pinili niyo pang maging kuripot kaysa bigyan ang mga estudyanteng willing maglaan ng oras para suportahan ang school.

At sa mga nakakuha ng ticket tapos binenta pa ng sobrang mahal—karma na lang sa inyo. Buti nga’t hindi kayo nakapasok. Saka niyo lang binaba ang presyo nung sarado na ang gate.

4. Scalpers are EVERYWHERE. Believe it or not, they will always find ways to sell tickets that were meant to be free, even to people outside UAAP schools. Para lang sa pera.

Additional info: You can’t enter without both a ticket and a school ID na proof na from UAAP school ka. So if you buy from scalpers and you’re not from a UAAP school, the ticket is basically useless. Sayang lang din. Napunta na sana sa ibang kapwa student.

I don’t usually write stuff like this, but I’ve been thinking about it for a while. Every time I check this page, I notice how many of the posts about being gay are written as jokes. Most of the time they’re sexual and every time I see it, I just feel sad. Maybe for a lot of you, it’s nothing. It’s just something to laugh at. But for someone like me (i’m bi) it doesn’t just disappear after reading it. It stays with me. It makes me think about how people in this school might look at me, or at anyone who’s not straight, and automatically reduce us to those same jokes. And it hurts in a way that’s hard to explain. Because the truth is, being gay isn’t about sex. It’s not about being dirty, or weird, or any of the things people here like to laugh about. It’s about love. It’s about finding comfort in yourself when the world makes it hard. It’s about liking someone in the same simple, human way that straight people do, but always with that extra layer of fear, fear that people will twist it into something disgusting.
I read the things people post and I just keep wondering if anyone thinks about what it feels like for us. To constantly see your identity turned into something shameful. To know that in the eyes of your classmates, maybe even your friends, you’ll always be some kind of punchline. It makes me feel small, and it makes me feel like no matter what I do, how hard I study or how kind I try to be, people will only ever see the joke, never the person.
I’m not writing this to call out anyone, or to pick a fight. I’m not even angry at all. I’m just tired. I’m tired of watching love get turned into something ugly when I know it isn’t. Maybe this won’t change anything. But maybe someone will read this and think twice. And for me, that would already mean a lot. Anyways, that's all for now. God bless you all

I hope this message serves as constructive feedback and a call for reflection on the performance of our institution.

1. Timely and Decisive Announcements
One of the most pressing concerns is the late announcement of class suspensions, particularly during severe weather or transportation strikes. Announcements often come too late, leaving students and professors unprepared. Not everyone has the financial or logistical flexibility to adjust last minute. Since a large portion of our community commutes from far areas such as Laguna, Bulacan, Rizal, and Cavite, early decisions are not just helpful, they are necessary. Students and faculty need ample time to plan their transportation, finances, and safety. Timely announcements are not a privilege but a right.

2. Facilities and Transparency
Another concern is the quality and consistency of our facilities. Elevators are frequently out of service, escalators are often shut down, and laboratories in multiple departments (engineering, biology, psychology, medical technology, hospital management, etc.) lack the quality expected of a university with rising tuition fees. Students deserve high-quality, reliable facilities.

This brings us to transparency: where does our tuition and fees allocation go? If maintenance issues persist despite increasing payments, then it is only fair that the student body is given clear insight into how funds are distributed, especially for infrastructure and maintenance. Students should not feel they are paying for substandard materials and short-term fixes.

These issues are not isolated grievances but widely shared experiences across the university community, as seen in student groups and forums. We hope the administration takes these concerns seriously and begins implementing long-term, student-centered solutions.

i've been doing well academically throughout my entire life. but i honestly don't know if i'd feel proud now that i am about to graduate with distinctions. 

it's not that i don't think i can legitimately do it, i know i can. i’ve proven that to myself in many ways. and yet despite that, i still resorted to academic dishonesty. it's not about wanting to be perceived smart or wanting to outperform others. the truth is, i’ve gotten to the point where i’m just tired. i don’t cheat because i’m incapable; i do it because i’m exhausted and i just want it to be over, with complete lack of interest in what i'm doing. maybe that's really the case, or maybe that's just what i'm telling myself.

it started with the pandemic, and just worsened more and more with the emergence of ai. maybe it's just me, or maybe it's the culture around me, but somewhere along the way, i stopped seeing the value in putting in extra effort for the same result. the pressure to keep up, to be that star student, to look perfect, and to constantly perform, especially when it feels like others around me are cutting corners too, has made it hard to care. what's the point in trying to do things "the right way", "the moral way", if people around me can get the same reward for less?

i don’t want to be stuck in this cycle, but at this point, i’m not sure how to get out of it.

To the Representative of One of the U-wide Organizations here at UE,

I'm reaching out to raise a serious and genuine concern—one that reflects not just the frustration of a friend of mine, but also the disappointment of students who expect more from their so-called "leaders."

I’ve seen your name pop up frequently in posts and comments, both on UE Freedom Wall and in the freshmen group. You seem very active online—but unfortunately, not in a way that reflects the responsibility that comes with being a student leader.

Recently, my friend anonymously posted on the UE Freedom Wall to express her deep frustration about tuition and her inability to attend classes because of the cancellation of classes and other circumstances. Instead of showing empathy or at least maintaining a respectful tone, you responded with inappropriate language—including curses—which is completely unacceptable, especially coming from someone who claims to represent a student organization.

Let me be blunt: if you cannot control how you speak online, you don’t deserve the title of a student leader. Leadership isn’t about popularity or presence—it’s about character, especially when no one is watching or when you're hiding behind a screen.

You might think it's “just social media,” but every post and every comment you make reflects directly on your organization, your co-officers, and your college. Right now, you’re not only dragging your own name down—you’re dragging others with you. That’s selfish, careless, and deeply disappointing.

I hope this serves as a wake-up call—not just to you, but to all student leaders who carry titles without carrying the integrity those titles demand.

Shout-out sa dalawang marites sa TYK Library (sa gilid sila nakaupo sa kabilang part ng lib) Friday ng 2:30pm ko 'to sinubmit, para malaman niyong kayo 'yon.

Grabe kayo. Ang lakas nyo mag-analyze ng ugali ng mga ibang tao like ang insensitive ni ganito, pero hindi nyo nare-realize na kayo mismo ang pinaka-insensitive sa buong floor. Paalala ko lang po, nasa library po tayo, kaya dapat common sense na tahimik. Imagine, andami naming nag-aaral at nagtatry maging productive para lang makapag-review bago midterms, tapos kailangan pa naming maki-share sa live chismis session niyo. Hindi po kasama sa tuition namin ang bayad para sa ingay niyo  at lalo na sa unsolicited tea na wala namang kinalaman sa amin.

Kung hindi nyo naman kayang mag-adjust ng volume sa boses nyo, BAKA NAMAN PWEDE KAYONG MAG-ADJUST NG LOCATION. Jusko ang dami namang spot na pwede pagchismisan, basta hindi dito kung saan lahat nagtatangkang mag-concentrate. Kung wala kayong balak mag-aral, at least huwag nyo kami idamay. Sobrang ironic lang ng ginagawa nyo, kasi habang nagrereklamo kayo tungkol sa pagiging "insensitive" ng ibang tao, kayo na mismo yung example ng pagiging sobrang insensitive. Sana sa susunod, bago mag-lecture tungkol sa ugali ng iba, matuto munang magbasa ng room.

BTW HABANG TINATYPE KO TO, YUNG ISA SA KANILA NAGPLAY NG VIDEO, TAPOS YUNG SOUND MAS MALAKAS PA SA BOSES NILA. 

Pakiusap, library po ito, hindi sinehan, kung gusto niyo po ng ganiyang ingay, malapit lang po ang SMGC, doon po kayo magmarathon.

Kung may iba pa pong katulad nila na pumapasok lang sa library para mag-ingay at mang-istorbo ng nasa paligid nila, itigil niyo na. Hindi po niyo kwarto ang library, hindi rin tambayan. Kung hindi nyo kayang irespeto yung silence na kailangan ng iba, mas mainam na huwag na kayong pumasok.

Hindi lahat ng tao may privilege magkaroon ng madaming free time, marami po sa amin nagso-solo at nagka-cram para lang makapasa sa exams. Nakakahiya na ang tanging ambag nyo ay mang-istorbo. KAILANGAN PA PO BA YANG SABIHIN AT IPAALALA SA INYO?

Next time, kung wala naman kayong balak mag-aral at magbasa, BASAHIN NIYO NALANG PO YUNG ATMOSPHERE.

As a UE Dentistry student and future dental professional, I feel deeply disappointed and frustrated about a recent issue in our clinics.

We work hard, day in and day out, to uphold the standards of our profession — from infection control to the quality of our clinical work — knowing that we’re dealing with real patients and real lives. That’s why it’s heartbreaking to hear about incidents of dishonesty, such as altering radiographs to make a procedure look perfect. This is not a harmless mistake; this is a serious ethical breach that can endanger patients and damage the reputation of our school.

What makes it worse is seeing the person involved continue to work in the clinics as if nothing happened. The confidence and audacity after committing such an act is discouraging for those of us who are trying to do things the right way. We strive to meet the standards honestly, yet situations like this make it feel like integrity isn’t valued as much as it should be.

UE College of Dentistry has always been proud of its reputation as a top-performing school. But reputation is built not only on passing rates but also on ethics, accountability, and professionalism. If incidents like this are ignored or excused, then we risk turning our standards into a mere showpiece. We owe it to our patients, our mentors, and ourselves to protect the credibility of this profession.

I’m speaking up because I care — about our school, our profession, and the trust our patients place in us. I hope our leaders take this seriously and demonstrate that integrity still matters in dentistry.

I really agree with this idea, thanks anon! Dentistry is a long and challenging six-year journey, and reaching the point of becoming clinicians is something truly worth celebrating. A recognition ceremony that includes our parents would mean so much—not just to us, but especially to them. They’ve been with us through every sleepless night, every breakdown, and every sacrifice.

Having them there to witness this milestone would make the journey feel lighter and more fulfilling. It’s not just our achievement—it’s theirs too. This kind of ceremony would remind us why we keep going, and it would give our parents the comfort and pride of knowing that all their sacrifices were worth it. More than a formality, it would be a moment of gratitude, recognition, and love shared between students and families who’ve walked this long path together.

Hi Anon, #that professor is notorious for being a pervert at madalas mamahiya sa klase. Honestly, surviving his class isn't really something to be proud of/brag about, like what other students says. Sobrang unfortunate at miserable mapunta sa ganyang prof who instill fear sa students instead of ACTUALLY encouraging them to learn, they are the "terror" profs na wala namang basis. I've come across different people from different courses who tried to report his actions sa PE Department or even change sections but nothing worked. I don't get bakit sobrang protektado niyan at hindi matanggal tanggal, ilang years niya na ginagawa. 

Honestly, para pakinggan reports niyo, kailangan niyo mag file pa ng complaint and magcollect ng a certain number of witnesses/victim to prove na he already did it multiple times. Isa ito sa mga rason kung bakit walang nakakapag step up, bukod sa takot, kulang ng evidence dahil hindi naman nila ineexpect na they would experience something like that sa PE class nila. It's just sad kasi some students are barely getting by in school tapos dadagdag pa yung ganyang prof. I never experienced humiliation from that prof firsthand, pero I've been into his class before and I can confirm na he always does that sa mga klase niya. Sinwerte lang ako na kaya ko idrop ang subject niya before. Becareful lang kasi kung makita niya ang post na to, baka lalo kayo pag initan. I'm sorry to hear what happened to your friend. I hope everyone who's been victimized by this prof gets the justice they deserve. He's done worse things before pa according to ue alumnis pero lagi siyang nakakalusot sa faculty.

Help… This isn’t really acad-related, pero I feel like I need someone to tell me the hard truth. I’m in a situationship right now, and things are kind of complicated. He’s actually my ex, pero we’re trying to patch things up since there were no cheating issues, just problems between us.

The thing is… I’ve kinda started feeling something for my friend. I can’t exactly pinpoint it, but I think he feels it too. None of us are saying anything because we don’t want to ruin anything. Pero ngayon pa lang, confused na ako… what more kapag inamin niya talaga yung totoo? Huhu. How do I stop this? Help.

To #UEFW24403
Sometimes, people are unaware na nakasakit sila dahil magkakaiba tayo talaga ng sensitivity. Probably, on their part it was nothing serious or for them it was funny so what we could do at this moment is to communicate or to educate the person directly then we decide on whether to continue the friendship or not based on their response regarding the matter. 

If after talking it out, ang response niya e galit pa siya instead of apologizing and trying to change, probably it was their ego talking. You’re probably dealing with a narcissist who can’t accept the fact that he/she is wrong. FO na pag ganyan. Mahirap makipag usap sa ganyan. 

What I’m trying to say is some people hurt people unintentionally and if there is lack of communication, they would never know the problem and fix it. I’m speaking from experience na nung nasaktan ako sa sharedpost ng ex girl best friend ko, instead of talking it out directly to her, sa ex boyfriend ko ako nag open up and he just blocked her instantly from my account. 

After months, she found out she was blocked and she was mad about it. I totally get why she felt that. Cinonfront niya ako using her dump account and on her perspective, that sharedpost was not for me and if kinausap ko lang siya, maiintindihan naman niya. She was unaware na maapektuhan ako sa post kasi akala niya ok na ako from that past trauma kasi matagal naman na raw yon and kapag kasama nila ako, mukhang okay na ako or healed. 

On my part, akala ko rin healed na ako nun pero distracted lang pala ako sa acads and friends ko kaya hindi ko yun naiisip pero nung nakita ko yung post, natrigger. Both sides are valid but I will admit that we are both partly wrong. 

I decided to still end the friendship based on how the confrontation went. Nagkakasakitan na kami verbally. It wasn’t healthy anymore and if ipipilit lang namin maging friends because sayang e ilang taon na kaming magkaibigan, baka the relationship we have will not be genuine anymore. Plastikan nalang ganon.

So to answer the question paano sila matututo? By letting them be aware of the situation and know how it made you feel. But sometimes, even communication can’t solve this if instead of listening and having empathy, ipagpilitan niyang wala naman siyang ginagawang mali.

i just needed to rant abt— and I’ll probably get hate from people who really pride UE Dent for this, but… honestly di ko gets yung hype. Laging sinasabi ng mga prof na dapat proud kami kasi top 1 school daw, pero rn di ko feel. First year pa lang ako (wala pa nga sa annex) tapos ang facilities parang meh para sa 180k for the whole year  ang sikip ng upuan, walang elevator, lagi pang off yung escalator. Wala pa TV, naaawa ako sa mga teachers kasi sila pa nagse-set up ng projector. Pati Labster at field trip, hiwalay pa bayad. Medyo OA ako dito pero yung gym sobrang init haha, akala ko de-aircon man lang kasi 180k per student tapos 12 sections naman you’d think all that money would go somewhere, pero parang wala lang.
 
 To be honest, the quality of teaching isn’t really what I expected either, some profs are kinda sabaw, to say the least. I came from a Big 4 school that had almost the same tuition, so paying this much here feels off. I’m not trying to sound like a bratty b*tch — maybe this is just me adjusting, and maybe over time I’ll learn to love it, especially since I really do enjoy the dentistry part itself. Maybe it’s just that some of the current subjects still feel too high-schoolish. And maybe, this really is the best Philippine dentistry can offer, and I should be thankful. Is it just me? How do you guys tolerate and survive in this environment cuz i honestly wanna switch schools nalang at this point.
 
 Just needed to let this out.

We were friends for years. I had a crush on her since Grade 7, and even when I liked others, I always went back to her. I knew her secrets, while she admired someone else. On her 17th birthday, I took the risk to show she’s the one I wanted. At first she opened up and gave me hope, but I fumbled when I talked about someone I dated before. She drifted away and eventually ghosted me.
Months later she came back, and things escalated quickly. After a fight, she asked for space, but I begged her to stay. She was busy as a Grade 12 student leader, burning out, and grieving her grandmother. Instead of being there, I cheated with my girl bestfriend. She didn’t know. We broke up two weeks before graduation before my flight to HK, and I unfairly blamed her for being unresponsive. A month later, she found out.
After that, nothing lasted for me. I dated others but always felt guilty, relapsing and checking her IG. Two years later, I saw how much she grew—more mature, stronger, more lovable—the one I wish I had treated better. Now she’s with someone else, and though I want her happy, I still hope I could find my way back into her life.
I hope you come back to me the way you came back to our Alma Mater. I miss you, Aly.

I would like to clarify that since I was the first person who raised the concern about the use of AI in pubmats, my intention was never to shame or target any specific organization. I submitted that post to spread awareness that relying on AI for pubmats is not acceptable, especially when we have many creative and talented students in UE who would be grateful for the opportunity to showcase their skills. Calling them out once is enough; I don’t see the need for others to add their own remarks by pointing out specific orgs or criticizing the quality of their pubmats. Let’s not forget to remain kind—since we are the older and more experienced ones, we should know how to approach these situations with respect and proper guidance. If you don’t like an org’s pubmats, it’s better to reach out to them directly rather than call them out publicly.

Replying to #UE24048

I beg to disagree. Please don’t falsely accuse someone—or a club—of using AI for their pubmats. If you're saying that kasi nag-downgrade yung quality ng pubmats, then I think they're trying their best to reach the level ng seniors nila. So, don’t invalidate their hard work by throwing accusations without proof or evidence.

I came across that first post about AI-made pubmats from SC orgs, and then suddenly other clubs were being dragged into the conversation. I just want to say this: not every well-designed output is AI-generated. Some people actually put in the time, effort, and creativity to make something good. Let’s not take that away from them just because the work looks polished.
It’s unfair—and honestly a bit careless—to throw around assumptions without knowing the full story. If you're going to call something out, make sure you're sure. Otherwise, you're just discrediting people who are doing their best.

I get that AI is a relevant issue right now, especially in creative work. And yes, we should talk about it. But let’s have those conversations with respect and mindfulness. Not everything needs to be a public call-out. There are better ways to raise concerns than pointing fingers and spreading assumptions.

At the end of the day, we’re all part of the same community. Let’s be kinder and a little more thoughtful with how we speak on these things.

I don’t get why the hate on people who cheat on exams is so big. Gets ko na hati pa rin opinion ng mga tao about this, pero can’t you guys just live your life without interfering with what others do? I’m not trying to defend cheating, but people often do something “for something”. 

Hindi natin alam kung ano ang pinagdadaanan ng isa’t isa, so why hate? In fact, sino pa bang hindi nag-cheat ngayong college? Para kayong mga high school kung magalit sa cheaters. We’re in our adult life now, and honestly, we don’t know what’s happening behind closed doors. Maybe may mga reasons sila why they needed to cheat. For sure, there are always internal factors na we’ll never even know. For me, it’s kinda immature to still hate on cheaters at this point. You can go on with your life by just minding your own business. It even teaches us a hard truth about life after school: people will do anything to survive. And kahit for you unfair ginagawa nila, you just have to live with it kasi that’s just how life is—unfair.

Look around, yung mga so-called student leaders? Nag-checheat din yan. Yung mga scholars? Nag-checheat din yan. And I’m not saying it’s okay, pero ano ngayon? Even your professors, don’t tell me none of them ever cheated in their courses before. Some profs I know openly admit na nag-cheat sila nung college, kasi to be honest, at some point, you really can’t survive without bending the rules.

So before you throw hate, maybe ask yourself, sa dami ng imperfections mo sa buhay, bakit ka nagagalit sa imperfections ng iba? Kasi at the end of the day, hindi ba mas productive kung ayusin mo na lang yung sarili mo kaysa manghusga?

“己所不欲，勿施于人。” 
“              .”

This saying comes from a lot of translated scriptures, but I chose the Chinese proverb from the Analects of Confucius because this was the first thing that was ever taught to me.

Why am I quoting this? It's because I want some of the Seniors of UE to learn this and apply it to their everyday lives. You can't expect that we would automatically respect you just because you're far more ahead than us. I would want people to understand that social ranking and power-tripping is such a toxic mindset. It diminishes the meaning of equality. I get that you've done more than us in the span of how many years you've studied in UE, but please treat us freshmen with respect. I'm not saying that all freshmen have respect as I am an avid reader of these freedom walls and I've read that there are some freshmen who think they're above than others. 

What I mean is, in general, I hope all people respect each other in order to have no complaints after this. 

RESPECT IS EARNED. 

I'm not mad, I'm just frustrated that some treat us like pure dogshit.

Sometimes, you just have to mature in life. Things comes and go as most people say. You feel like giving up and just ending it all there and then. But you know yourself that you still have some worth. You make mistakes, you learn from them. A friendship ends and you made enemies in the process? Find someone else that will accept you as is. As my mother says it "Pag ayaw niya edi wag. Intindihin mo muna ang sarili mo bago ang iba." It's a strong phrase to say for sure. That's what I learnt from all of my countless failures. It's that you yourself, should be able to find who you really are. No people can determine that. It's not always going to be the same "hey I'd like to experience that as well" sort of thing everytime. It all just boils down to how you're going to balance yourself, and what I mean by that is trying to get that very balance between leaving behind the things that made you who you are to fit in with everyone else, while still being able to keep those same factors that made you who you are in the first place. While this might be yet another one of those posts, it still feels refreshing getting to share my current process growing as a person. I guess I don't have a final remark in mind, but I guess just try to focus on what's Infront of you first, try to focus with your relationship with yourself. This is a message not only to people out there but to myself as well.

This post is not intended to offend anybody but is instead an attempt to maybe show others that they still have worth.

It honestly hurts when the people who should be setting the example are the ones mocking us. We’re not even sure that post was made by a sophomore, because I haven’t seen any of my batchmates wearing white shoes in annex. What I’ve seen are dent students in LB wearing them.

But let’s be real, this isn’t just about shoes. This is about respect and character. Is this what UE CDent really represents? A community that chooses to tear each other down instead of lift each other up? That disregards the values and honor we’re supposed to carry? It’s discouraging, and honestly, it’s sad. Because at the end of the day, it really be your own people who bring you down.

To my fellow sophomores: let’s not fall into the same trap. Let’s keep practicing proper etiquette in annex. We’ve got a long journey ahead, and clashing with our seniors over petty things is just wasted energy. Respect goes both ways, we give it, we should get it back. Respect will always be reciprocated. 

And to whoever thought it was okay to belittle irregular students, stop. That mindset is cruel and out of touch. People go through different struggles, and some are just doing everything they can to keep moving forward. Not everyone has the privilege of a straight path. Some are struggling every single day just to make ends meet, just to stay afloat.  Being irregular doesn’t make anyone less. Looking down on them doesn’t make you better, it just shows your lack of compassion. Remember, life has a way of giving back what you put out.

We all wear the same institution on our uniforms. That should mean something. Don’t be the reason that name loses its weight.

Friendly reminder lang sa mga CDent lower years: huwag lumabas ng annex na naka-lab gown. Yung lab gown ninyo ay personal barrier yan laban sa iba’t ibang hazardous substances na ginagamit natin araw-araw, at para na rin sa infection control. Hindi kayo nilalahat, pero napupuna kayo kasi may mga matitigas pa rin ang ulo.

Hindi rason na nagmamadali o hassle na alisin pa kaya hinayaan na lang na suot outside annex ha. Madadala nyo yan sa clinic years ninyo kaya pakiusap, sumunod kayo sa protocol.

In regards sa UECD uniform decorum:

Bilang isang alum and graduate, sa totoo lang you guys have it good pagdating sa uniform. Let me share this lang tutal napaguusapan naman.

Once upon a time, sa mga lalakeng magpupursue ng Dent, white polo na 3 pockets na ang butones sa gitna nagsisimula, BLUE pants, black shoes (legit di mo ramdam na belong ka sa UECD nun, Predent days)

After nun, Dent Proper ka na! Congrats! Uniform mo same style polo, white pants, BLACK shoes (medyo belong, pero with the black shoes medyo hindi parin)

Uyyyy 3rd year ka na! Clinician ka na! Puti na sapatos mo pero everything else is the same.

Graduating na din finally, that's when magbabago yung polo into the side button thing, yung poging unis na inaasam mo all your dental life.

So ano ang purpose ng post na ito? Mema lang ba?

Perspective lang na before kami nakakuha ng uniforms na ganun, we paid our dues.

Sana yung mga sumusuway, pay your dues muna. Promise, mas satisfying yung uniform change or update kapag narealize mo yung challenges na nilagpasan mo para makuha yung inaasam mong wardrobe.

Yun lang naman. Be respectful lang. Sunod nalang tayo, okay? Wag na pabida.

Oh, and btw, irreg ba? For the record di lahat ng taong irreg bagsak sa subjects, minsan malas lang talaga sa chair time and requirements. Iba-iba yan, you're being trained to be professionals so maaga palang sana start nyo na idevelop sarili nyo into being better.

Sige ka, baka mamaya magopen ka first case mo RCT 11x kang reject (that was me, took me a sem kaya ako nadelay)

Oh siya. Maliit ang mundo ng dent, let's all be nice and respectful, okay?

Good eve! I'm an Accountancy Student here in UE.
I just want to express my deepest gratitude towards my blockmates, professors, 
and the people who make this university possible.

In my whole academic life, I have never truly cared for academics,
Nor have I felt open to people for conversations.
This time around, with the people I'm with,
I felt that it's time for me to care, time for me to strive, to be serious,
show the world that this university is not like any other.

Students here in UE Manila are so kind!
I'm glad that I was told that this place was different from other universities,
Because it was very true, ranging to our student council, univerisity organizations, 
and even the staffs!

Proud to be in BAA with the most amazing blockmates!
I can see us in these following years working hard and bouncing back to push through.
but its also worth it, because I also see all our names on the top of the Board Exam pass list, I can see us receiving our certificates and all the medals swinging as we walk forward.

Let's put Accountancy back on top!
